Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

My Meme

My meme may appeal to some people because it pokes fun at the absurdity of some of our thoughts and fears, it depicts this through an unrealistic, exaggerated hypothetical situation in our minds.

library(magick)

# Read in images and resize to same dimensions
meme1 <- image_read("meme1.png") %>% 
  image_resize("500x500")
meme2 <- image_read("meme2.png") %>% 
  image_resize("500x500")

# square 1
meme1 <- image_read("meme1.png") %>%
  image_scale(500)

# square 2
text1 <- image_blank(width= 500,
                  height = 500,
                  color = "#FFFFFF") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "I wonder if he's thinking of me",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 20,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# square 3
meme2 <- image_read("meme2.png") %>%
  image_scale(500)

#square 4
text2 <- image_blank(width= 500,
                  height = 500,
                  color = "#FFFFFF") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "if i dont lift this my whole family dies",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 20,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "center")

# combine top row
top_row <- image_append(c(meme1, text1))

# combine bottom row
bottom_row <- image_append(c(meme2, text2))
                        
# combine top and bottom rows together
meme <- c(top_row, bottom_row) %>%
          image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
          image_scale(750)

# Save meme as a PNG file
image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")

My animated GIF

My animated GIF consists of 4 unique blue ball emojis each displaying different emotions, together as an animation it forms a short GIF that shows the progression of human emotions when someone receives some CRAZY news. 

# load magick package
library

# creating each frame
frame1 <- image_read("frame1.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame2 <- image_read("frame2.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame3 <- image_read("frame3.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)
frame4 <- image_read("frame4.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)

# combine all frames together in order using a vector
combined_frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)

# creating an animation
animation <- image_animate(combined_frames, fps = 1)

# save animation as GIF file
image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
